So I enrolled at
Boston University.

00:01:02.730 --> 00:01:04.260
My dad then moved to NIH.

00:01:04.260 --> 00:01:06.210
Both my parents
are deceased now.

00:01:06.210 --> 00:01:08.400
But the Boston area
is very special to us

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:10.200
because it was the
first place that we

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:14.490
lived in this great and
wonderful country of ours.

00:01:14.490 --> 00:01:16.410
And then, I'm very,
very happy to be back

00:01:16.410 --> 00:01:19.260
as a guest of Professor Lippert,
and the students in his class,

00:01:19.260 --> 00:01:21.000
and the colleagues.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.363
And I promise you a good
time, if you pay attention.

00:01:23.363 --> 00:01:24.229
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:26.269 --> 00:01:27.810
So what I really
would like you to do

00:01:27.810 --> 00:01:30.210
is sit back and
relax because I'm

00:01:30.210 --> 00:01:33.630
going to share with
you, to begin with,

00:01:33.630 --> 00:01:36.390
some important convictions
about what it is that we do

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:40.350
in science and why we do it.

00:01:40.350 --> 00:01:42.540
I wish I had more
time to go in depth.

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:47.400
But I just want to go
quickly through some

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:51.370
of these convictions
that I hold very deeply.

00:01:51.370 --> 00:01:54.999
So let's see if this
is going to work here.

00:01:54.999 --> 00:01:56.040
I want to see your faces.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:56.540
OK.

00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:00.130
I can still see your faces.

00:02:00.130 --> 00:02:02.750
So Science is Fun and
the Joy of Learning.

00:02:02.750 --> 00:02:04.320
That's the title
of my presentation,

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.440
Science is Fun and
the Joy of Learning.

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:09.960
And every word is
carefully selected.

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:12.040
You know, English is
my second language.

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:15.810
So I think about every
word and its meaning.

00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:17.760
I also want to say that
it's a pleasure for me

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:21.900
to see some old friends here,
but also to make new friends.

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:26.190
And to see someone who
watched me in Singapore, when

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:27.437
I was in Singapore--

00:02:27.437 --> 00:02:28.020
Where are you?

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:29.910
Right there, yeah, yeah--

00:02:29.910 --> 00:02:31.320
about three years ago.

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:35.670
So welcome.

00:02:35.670 --> 00:02:42.040
So what I'd like to
say to you immediately,

00:02:42.040 --> 00:02:45.750
that your brain
and my brain will

00:02:45.750 --> 00:02:48.720
be different after
this presentation,

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:50.820
if you pay attention.

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:54.750
If you don't pay attention,
I can't do much about it.

00:02:54.750 --> 00:03:00.930
But both my brain and your
brain will be different.

00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:05.040
35, 40 years ago, when students
went to medical school,

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:07.880
they were told that
the brain is an organ.

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:10.200
It doesn't change very much.

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:11.890
But now we know more.

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:14.910
Through the neurosciences,
we know a lot more.

00:03:14.910 --> 00:03:17.280
We know about plasticity.

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.890
In fact, changes in
the brain happen.

00:03:19.890 --> 00:03:22.090
That's what education
is all about.

00:03:22.090 --> 00:03:25.290
That's what learning is about,
if those changes were not

00:03:25.290 --> 00:03:26.560
happening.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:30.210
So I just want to share with
you the importance of being

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:32.430
focused and paying attention.

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:38.150
We live in the most advanced
society in humankind.

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:40.610
And these advances are
due to advances in science

00:03:40.610 --> 00:03:43.580
and in technology.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:47.360
I want you to think of
this statement I just made.

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:49.610
Everything we enjoy
now is the result

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:52.430
of advances in science
and in technology.

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:54.890
The advances are so
great, much greater

00:03:54.890 --> 00:03:57.380
than we knew 50 years
ago when I first

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:01.100
came to this country,
or a hundred years ago,

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:05.150
or 200 years ago, or 500 years
ago, a thousand years ago.

00:04:05.150 --> 00:04:10.400
A long time ago,
technology drove society.

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:12.680
The printing press was invented.

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:17.899
Electricity lit the world before
we learned about the electron,

00:04:17.899 --> 00:04:19.700
before the electron
was discovered.

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:21.260
There are all kinds
of connections

00:04:21.260 --> 00:04:23.480
between science and technology.

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:27.950
But nowadays, it's science
that drives technology.

00:04:27.950 --> 00:04:29.420
Our ancestors were very good.

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:30.260
They built cities.

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:31.370
They built canals.

00:04:31.370 --> 00:04:33.020
They built pyramids.

00:04:33.020 --> 00:04:35.520
But now, we can build
pyramids at the atomic level.

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:37.460
You've seen pictures of them.

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:40.310
A great deal of
wonderful transformations

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:43.430
have happened because
of advances in science

00:04:43.430 --> 00:04:45.230
and in technology.

00:04:45.230 --> 00:04:49.660
And it is the brain,
our brain, that is

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:52.640
responsible for those changes.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:57.010
We're all capable of doing
good things, each one of us.

00:04:57.010 --> 00:05:00.730
And each one of us is
capable of doing evil.

00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:03.340
And that's why we have
to be selective about how

00:05:03.340 --> 00:05:06.070
we use the results of
those advances in science

00:05:06.070 --> 00:05:07.450
and in technology.

00:05:07.450 --> 00:05:10.090
These are different parts
of the control mechanisms

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:13.390
that we know about
now for the brain.

00:05:13.390 --> 00:05:18.480
So please pay attention
and bear with me.

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:21.120
You came to see some experiments
and some demonstrations.

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:22.450
I promise I will get to them.

00:05:22.450 --> 00:05:23.302
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:23.302 --> 00:05:24.510
I promise I will get to them.

00:05:24.510 --> 00:05:29.280
But I want you to understand
the perspective and the context

00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:32.400
for doing those experiments
and those demonstrations.

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:35.460
So we all like to
say that chemistry

00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:36.640
is the central science.

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:38.700
And it is the central science.

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:41.592
I like to say it's
the familiar science.

00:05:41.592 --> 00:05:43.050
In fact, what I'd
like to say, it's

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:46.290
the science of the familiar
because everything around us

00:05:46.290 --> 00:05:47.910
is made of chemicals.

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:49.740
The air that we
breathe is a mixture

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:51.900
of usually good chemicals.

00:05:51.900 --> 00:05:54.000
The food that we eat is
a mixture of chemicals.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.610
The clothes that we wear
are made of chemicals.

00:05:56.610 --> 00:05:58.710
Our own bodies are
made of chemicals.

00:05:58.710 --> 00:06:00.240
What goes on inside
our bodies is

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:03.450
nothing but a series of
biochemical reactions.

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:06.210
The medicine that we
take when we are sick

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:07.490
is a mixture of chemicals.

00:06:10.390 --> 00:06:12.540
The drugs that some
people very stupidly

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:15.195
experiment with are chemicals.

00:06:15.195 --> 00:06:16.380
Ah, some of you are smiling.

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:19.810
I'm connecting with the already.

00:06:19.810 --> 00:06:22.700
That's why we need to
learn about chemicals,

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:26.560
their proper handling, safe
handling, proper disposal,

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:27.520
their benefits.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:30.280
It's so complex,
but it's beautiful.

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:31.660
Beauty is part of science.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:34.585
It's an essential
part of science.

00:06:34.585 --> 00:06:36.460
Now having told you that
everything around us

00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:38.668
is made of chemicals, I'd
like to ask each one of you

00:06:38.668 --> 00:06:40.910
right now to reach out.

00:06:40.910 --> 00:06:42.430
It's OK, Lou.

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:45.088
It's part of the effect.

00:06:45.088 --> 00:06:46.870
It already had the
same effect on you.

00:06:46.870 --> 00:06:48.280
So that's good.

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:50.104
I'd like to ask each
one of you right now

00:06:50.104 --> 00:06:51.520
to reach out and
touch a chemical.

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:53.220
Go ahead and do it right now.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:54.970
Somebody's tapping on
somebody's shoulder.

00:06:54.970 --> 00:06:56.140
Somebody's is pulling
somebody's hair.

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:57.220
Don't pull it too long.

00:06:57.220 --> 00:06:58.810
Somebody is reaching
out in the air.

00:06:58.810 --> 00:06:59.309
Yes.

00:06:59.309 --> 00:07:00.770
Chemicals are all around us.

00:07:00.770 --> 00:07:05.470
And we want to learn and enjoy
the beautiful chemical world

00:07:05.470 --> 00:07:06.160
that we live in.

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:10.120
That's why I say chemistry is
the science of the familiar.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:13.120
It's the science
of the familiar.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:16.960
So I want to share with you
for just a few short seconds

00:07:16.960 --> 00:07:20.920
the theme that I have selected
for the American Chemical

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:21.620
Society.

00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:24.160
As Professor Lippert said,
I will be the president

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:25.415
beginning January 1.

00:07:25.415 --> 00:07:27.040
But I'm not waiting
till then because I

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:29.810
want to get a good head
start and get going.

00:07:29.810 --> 00:07:31.900
The theme I selected
is advancing chemistry,

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:34.750
communicating chemistry;
advancing chemistry,

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:38.290
communicating chemistry;
advancing chemistry,

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:40.450
communicating chemistry.

00:07:40.450 --> 00:07:42.730
And I want to call your
attention to the ACS mission

00:07:42.730 --> 00:07:44.800
statement.

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:46.840
One of the worst things
that a presenter can do

00:07:46.840 --> 00:07:48.879
is show a slide and
then proceed to read it.

00:07:48.879 --> 00:07:50.170
It's an insult to the audience.

00:07:50.170 --> 00:07:51.250
You can read it.

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:52.016
But forgive me.

00:07:52.016 --> 00:07:53.140
I don't mean to insult you.

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:56.320
I want to share with you
the emphasis about this.

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:00.130
So it says, "To advance the
broader chemistry enterprise

00:08:00.130 --> 00:08:03.670
and its practitioners
for the benefit of Earth

00:08:03.670 --> 00:08:05.120
and its people."

00:08:05.120 --> 00:08:09.190
Such a profound statement, I
only wish I had written it.

00:08:09.190 --> 00:08:12.270
And then there's the ACS vision,
"Improving people's lives

00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:14.440
through the transforming
power of chemistry."

00:08:14.440 --> 00:08:16.900
"Transform" is a
very powerful word.

00:08:16.900 --> 00:08:20.350
That's what happens to us
when we become educated.

00:08:20.350 --> 00:08:23.620
This is what happens to us when
we become learned individuals.

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:26.050
This is what happens
to societies when they

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:27.640
become advanced and learned.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:31.050
They are transformed.

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:33.419
I've selected four initiatives.

00:08:33.419 --> 00:08:35.309
Next year is the
sesquicentennial

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:37.140
of the Land Grant Act.

00:08:37.140 --> 00:08:38.850
And the Land Grant
Act, as some of you

00:08:38.850 --> 00:08:41.580
know, and I'm about to tell
you if you didn't know it,

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:44.580
transformed America.

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:46.710
MIT is a land grant institution.

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:47.532
Did you know that?

00:08:47.532 --> 00:08:49.740
Raise your hand if you knew
that MIT was a land grant

00:08:49.740 --> 00:08:50.350
institution.

00:08:50.350 --> 00:08:51.270
OK.

00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:54.060
Raise your hand now if you
know that MIT is a land grant

00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:55.490
institution?

00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:56.460
Everybody-- right?

00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:58.620
I mean, look, I asked
you to pay attention.

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:00.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:02.292
I said your brains
will be different.

00:09:02.292 --> 00:09:03.750
My brain is being
different already

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:05.374
because I can tell
from your reactions,

00:09:05.374 --> 00:09:09.420
when it is visual reactions,
and also from your sound

00:09:09.420 --> 00:09:11.160
that you're sharing with me.

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:14.220
So we're going to mark the
sesquicentennial of the Land

00:09:14.220 --> 00:09:18.600
Grant Act at the national
ACS meeting in San Diego

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:21.480
and Philadelphia by
looking retrospectively

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:24.750
at what chemistry departments
have done in the past 150

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:25.440
years.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:27.880
So we educate ourselves
about our heritage.

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:29.422
What I'm really most
interested in is

00:09:29.422 --> 00:09:31.463
what we're going to do in
the future, what you're

00:09:31.463 --> 00:09:32.550
going to do in the future?

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:34.450
I'm not going to be
around much longer.

00:09:34.450 --> 00:09:35.380
I hope a long time.

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:37.290
But not as long as
you're going to be.

00:09:37.290 --> 00:09:39.180
So we want to be prospective.

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:41.190
We want a glance in
the real view mirror.

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:43.440
But we want to look
ahead so we can

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:47.190
be participants and leaders
in transformations that

00:09:47.190 --> 00:09:50.440
are good for our human society.

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:54.540
Our second initiative deals
with appointing a blue ribbon

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:58.087
commission to examine the
purposes of graduate education

00:09:58.087 --> 00:09:59.670
and research in the
chemical sciences.

00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:01.200
Look at the purposes.

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:05.160
Why do we have graduate programs
in the chemical sciences?

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:07.560
Has the German model
served us well?

00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:10.399
Is it appropriate
for the 21st century?

00:10:10.399 --> 00:10:11.940
We make promises to
graduate students

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:13.356
when they come to
graduate school.

00:10:13.356 --> 00:10:15.210
Do we keep those promises?

00:10:15.210 --> 00:10:17.880
Look at the duration of the
postdoctoral appointment now.

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:19.630
It's getting longer and longer.

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:21.420
So we talk about
employment issues.

00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:24.060
We also look at the profile
of the graduate students,

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:27.930
diversity, as well
as international part

00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:29.320
of the profile.

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:31.890
And we want to, of
course, remember

00:10:31.890 --> 00:10:34.620
that the graduate students
were undergraduates before.

00:10:34.620 --> 00:10:36.767
And before that, they
were in precollege.

00:10:36.767 --> 00:10:38.100
So we're going to segue to that.

00:10:38.100 --> 00:10:42.180
But the focus is on
this level right now.

00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:44.130
There'll be listening sessions.

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:47.780
There'll be opportunities to
interact via email, webinars,

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:50.190
with this blue ribbon commission
that I have appointed.

00:10:50.190 --> 00:10:52.710
The third initiative is to
help the public understand

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:54.900
the science of climate change.

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:57.990
The science of climate
change, not the politics,

00:10:57.990 --> 00:11:01.050
not the economics, but the
science of climate change.

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:02.520
What is a greenhouse gas?

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:04.290
What makes it a greenhouse gas?

00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:07.650
Did you know that any molecule
with three atoms or more

00:11:07.650 --> 00:11:09.590
in the gaseous phase
is a greenhouse gas?

00:11:09.590 --> 00:11:10.500
Did you know that?

00:11:10.500 --> 00:11:11.040
Yes or no?

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:12.240
Did you know that?

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:13.350
You didn't know it, right.

00:11:13.350 --> 00:11:15.180
Well, I just told you.

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:15.900
OK.

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:18.540
Every molecule in
the gaseous phase,

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:21.750
that has three atoms or
more, is a greenhouse gas.

00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:24.360
But they're not all effective.

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:25.980
And why aren't
they all effective?

00:11:25.980 --> 00:11:27.990
And what does it
take for a molecule

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:29.550
to become a greenhouse gas?

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:31.361
We all know about
dipole moments.

00:11:31.361 --> 00:11:31.860
Yes.

00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:32.940
You know about dipole moments?

00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:33.480
OK.

00:11:33.480 --> 00:11:35.520
So what I'd like you to do is
make connections between what

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:37.110
you know and what
you're hearing me

00:11:37.110 --> 00:11:39.660
say now because
that's how we learn.

