to sort out the information, and
be very careful about it, so we

00:22:33.220 --> 00:22:35.620
have the proper interpretation.

00:22:35.620 --> 00:22:36.990
So this is when I cover it now.

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:39.190
You see this shadow
cannot be seen.

00:22:39.190 --> 00:22:41.560
And that's how we
started with it.

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:43.406
So we have to make connections.

00:22:43.406 --> 00:22:44.780
We have to make
good connections.

00:22:44.780 --> 00:22:46.660
We don't want to have
any impedance problems.

00:22:46.660 --> 00:22:48.370
That's what we
don't want to have.

00:22:48.370 --> 00:22:51.910
And I want to show
you why we want

00:22:51.910 --> 00:22:54.550
to do experiments
and demonstrations,

00:22:54.550 --> 00:22:57.570
why we want to be engaging.

00:22:57.570 --> 00:22:59.730
This is why.

00:22:59.730 --> 00:23:01.510
That's why.

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:03.300
That's why.

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:05.260
That's why.

00:23:05.260 --> 00:23:06.440
That's why.

00:23:06.440 --> 00:23:07.990
You just look at those faces.

00:23:07.990 --> 00:23:10.620
You just look at those faces.

00:23:10.620 --> 00:23:13.510
And each one of them is engaged.

00:23:13.510 --> 00:23:14.790
Engagement is important.

00:23:14.790 --> 00:23:17.480
But what's really important
is what happens after that.

00:23:17.480 --> 00:23:20.440
So we're going to
now get into what

00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:23.260
happens as you become engaged.

00:23:23.260 --> 00:23:24.700
Lights out, please.

00:23:24.700 --> 00:23:27.670
Because we're going to do
some experiments, in addition

00:23:27.670 --> 00:23:29.031
to the one we did.

00:23:29.031 --> 00:23:29.530
Yes.

00:23:29.530 --> 00:23:29.800
Yes.

00:23:29.800 --> 00:23:31.050
I know you've waited too long.

00:23:31.050 --> 00:23:31.710
I know.

00:23:31.710 --> 00:23:32.770
I know.

00:23:32.770 --> 00:23:35.500
When we do experiments, we'll
obey all the safety rules.

00:23:35.500 --> 00:23:36.880
You notice I have my goggles on.

00:23:36.880 --> 00:23:38.290
Did you notice that?

00:23:38.290 --> 00:23:39.919
I just pointed it
out as a reminder.

00:23:39.919 --> 00:23:42.460
For those of you who noticed
and those of you who didn't, you

00:23:42.460 --> 00:23:44.537
just saw that I have them on.

00:23:44.537 --> 00:23:46.120
I have a fire
extinguisher right here.

00:23:46.120 --> 00:23:48.760
It's ready to be used, just
in case something goes out

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:49.587
of control.

00:23:49.587 --> 00:23:51.670
I'm not planning on anything
going out of control.

00:23:51.670 --> 00:23:54.790
But we have it as a
safety precaution.

00:23:54.790 --> 00:24:00.370
So what I'm going to do is
take a match and strike it.

00:24:03.490 --> 00:24:04.720
You like that, right?

00:24:04.720 --> 00:24:05.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:08.370
So this is an example of what
we call a combustion reaction.

00:24:08.370 --> 00:24:10.800
I'm going to light a candle.

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:11.790
And--

00:24:11.790 --> 00:24:12.590
AUDIENCE: Whoa.

00:24:12.590 --> 00:24:15.990
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: --I'm
going to-- whoa is right, see.

00:24:15.990 --> 00:24:17.832
Engagement.

00:24:17.832 --> 00:24:19.290
I want to tell you
something that I

00:24:19.290 --> 00:24:20.498
have observed over the years.

00:24:20.498 --> 00:24:23.790
I've been doing these
demonstrations for over 40

00:24:23.790 --> 00:24:25.050
years.

00:24:25.050 --> 00:24:28.200
Youngsters and people
in retirement homes

00:24:28.200 --> 00:24:31.650
are not inhibited
like the rest of us.

00:24:31.650 --> 00:24:34.900
So we have to allow ourselves
to express ourselves.

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:38.170
So this is an example of
a combustion reaction.

00:24:38.170 --> 00:24:44.770
And it is, of course,
related to Michael Faraday.

00:24:44.770 --> 00:24:47.190
You know who Michael
Faraday was, right?

00:24:47.190 --> 00:24:49.800
He used to gather young
people around Christmas time

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:52.630
at the Royal Institution and
do experiments with them.

00:24:52.630 --> 00:24:54.610
And one of his most
famous lectures

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:57.750
is on the chemical
history of the candle.

00:24:57.750 --> 00:24:59.610
So what I'm going to
do now, because you're

00:24:59.610 --> 00:25:02.940
paying good attention,
I'm going to reach back

00:25:02.940 --> 00:25:05.580
into my back pocket
and get my wallet out.

00:25:05.580 --> 00:25:07.683
What do people usually
keep in their wallets?

00:25:07.683 --> 00:25:08.410
AUDIENCE: Money.

00:25:08.410 --> 00:25:08.650
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Money.

00:25:08.650 --> 00:25:09.302
What else?

00:25:09.302 --> 00:25:10.260
AUDIENCE: Credit cards.

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:10.900
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Credit cards.

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:11.340
What else?

00:25:11.340 --> 00:25:12.120
AUDIENCE: Driver's license.

00:25:12.120 --> 00:25:12.840
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Driver's license,

00:25:12.840 --> 00:25:14.220
if you're old
enough to have one.

00:25:14.220 --> 00:25:14.670
What else?

00:25:14.670 --> 00:25:15.330
AUDIENCE: Pictures.

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:16.600
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Pictures,
all kinds of things.

00:25:16.600 --> 00:25:19.016
So what I'm going to do now
is I'm going to reach in here.

00:25:19.016 --> 00:25:20.730
I'm going to take a
dollar bill and I'm

00:25:20.730 --> 00:25:23.650
going to put it into the
flame, just like that.

00:25:23.650 --> 00:25:24.667
AUDIENCE: Wow.

00:25:24.667 --> 00:25:26.250
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Was that too fast?

00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:26.660
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:25:26.660 --> 00:25:28.493
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Well, I asked you to pay

00:25:28.493 --> 00:25:29.950
close attention, didn't I?

00:25:29.950 --> 00:25:33.810
I'm trying to engage your brain.

00:25:33.810 --> 00:25:37.072
So that was not a
real dollar bill.

00:25:37.072 --> 00:25:38.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:38.250 --> 00:25:40.970
That was a fake dollar bill.

00:25:40.970 --> 00:25:43.290
That was a phony dollar bill.

00:25:43.290 --> 00:25:46.250
It's called flash paper.

00:25:46.250 --> 00:25:50.060
What we always do in science
is repeat the experiment.

00:25:50.060 --> 00:25:52.450
So I take out what looks
like a dollar bill.

00:25:52.450 --> 00:25:54.110
But it's not a real dollar bill.

00:25:54.110 --> 00:25:55.560
I bring it close to the flame.

00:26:03.272 --> 00:26:05.300
It disappears into thin air.

00:26:05.300 --> 00:26:08.060
It looks like magic.

00:26:08.060 --> 00:26:10.190
I love magic.

00:26:10.190 --> 00:26:15.040
Magic is engaging,
but not informative.

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:17.590
Magic is engaging.

00:26:17.590 --> 00:26:20.590
So this is paper that has
been treated with chemicals so

00:26:20.590 --> 00:26:23.350
that when it burns, it
doesn't leave any ash behind.

00:26:23.350 --> 00:26:25.290
It's called flash paper.

00:26:25.290 --> 00:26:28.180
And so what are the chemicals
that are used for this?

00:26:28.180 --> 00:26:29.680
You want to think
about this, right.

00:26:29.680 --> 00:26:32.560
So you want to educate yourself
about it if you want to.

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:34.789
And you might want
to go to my website

00:26:34.789 --> 00:26:35.830
to learn more about this.

00:26:35.830 --> 00:26:37.325
How do you get to my website?

00:26:37.325 --> 00:26:38.972
AUDIENCE: www.funsci.org.

00:26:38.972 --> 00:26:39.930
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: OK.

00:26:39.930 --> 00:26:41.100
You got it.

00:26:41.100 --> 00:26:43.350
So now I would
like to ask someone

00:26:43.350 --> 00:26:45.030
in the audience to
volunteer to help me

00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:45.870
with the next experiment.

00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:46.620
Who wants to help?

00:26:46.620 --> 00:26:49.095
Well, let me tell you first
what I need help with, OK.

00:26:49.095 --> 00:26:50.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:54.300
I'd like someone in the audience
to let me borrow from them

00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:55.920
a real $1 bill.

00:26:55.920 --> 00:26:57.420
Is there someone
in the audience who

00:26:57.420 --> 00:26:58.795
would let me--
who would trust me

00:26:58.795 --> 00:27:02.340
with a real $1
bill or a $5 bill?

00:27:02.340 --> 00:27:04.290
Steve, how about
a $20 bill, huh?

00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:06.650
You got a $20 bill?

00:27:06.650 --> 00:27:07.150
OK.

00:27:07.150 --> 00:27:08.490
Here's a $1 bill.

00:27:08.490 --> 00:27:09.660
It's a real $1 bill.

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:11.940
You know what I'm going
to do with it, don't you?

00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:14.640
You know where this is going.

00:27:14.640 --> 00:27:17.100
So combustion, combustion is--

00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:18.405
AUDIENCE: You did say borrow.

00:27:18.405 --> 00:27:18.840
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Huh?

00:27:18.840 --> 00:27:20.048
AUDIENCE: You did say borrow.

00:27:20.048 --> 00:27:21.640
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
I did say borrow.

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:22.780
You know what?

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:26.430
That's a very important
observation that you made

00:27:26.430 --> 00:27:28.260
and you are reporting it.

00:27:28.260 --> 00:27:33.480
Because the whole exchange
for the benefit of society

00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:36.240
works on the element of trust.

00:27:36.240 --> 00:27:39.720
You trusted me
with this $1 bill.

00:27:39.720 --> 00:27:42.710
So I did say borrow, which
means I'm going to give it back.

00:27:42.710 --> 00:27:43.439
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:27:43.439 --> 00:27:44.980
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
I didn't say what

00:27:44.980 --> 00:27:47.195
form it's going to be
in when I give it back.

00:27:47.195 --> 00:27:48.185
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:50.170 --> 00:27:53.290
So, well, I have
a jar right here.

00:27:53.290 --> 00:27:55.992
And I have in this jar--

00:27:55.992 --> 00:27:56.950
what does it look like?

00:27:56.950 --> 00:27:57.470
I have a liquid.

00:27:57.470 --> 00:27:58.240
What does it look like?

00:27:58.240 --> 00:27:58.900
It looks like?

00:27:58.900 --> 00:27:59.260
AUDIENCE: Water.

00:27:59.260 --> 00:28:00.926
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
It looks like water.

00:28:00.926 --> 00:28:02.890
The way we described this
liquid is to say it's

00:28:02.890 --> 00:28:06.490
a clear and colorless liquid,
which is what water is.

00:28:06.490 --> 00:28:10.320
So I'm going to take
this liquid and--

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:12.820
so I want everybody to
see the jar right here,

00:28:12.820 --> 00:28:14.730
get this out of the way.

00:28:14.730 --> 00:28:17.490
I'm going to take
the dollar bill.

00:28:17.490 --> 00:28:21.060
I'm going to soak it in this
clear and colorless liquid,

00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:23.210
which looks like water.

00:28:23.210 --> 00:28:26.640
And I'm going to fish it
out using those tongs.

00:28:26.640 --> 00:28:28.839
You see, it's dripping
like any wet object would.

00:28:28.839 --> 00:28:30.630
And then I'm going to
take it to the flame.

00:28:30.630 --> 00:28:31.780
Take a good look at it now.

00:28:31.780 --> 00:28:33.510
It may be last time you see it.

00:28:33.510 --> 00:28:38.692
So here is the dollar
bill on fire, or is it?

00:28:38.692 --> 00:28:39.482
AUDIENCE: No.

00:28:39.482 --> 00:28:41.815
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: But you
did see a flame, didn't you?

00:28:41.815 --> 00:28:42.280
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:28:42.280 --> 00:28:44.920
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: So now I ask
you, can this liquid be water?

00:28:44.920 --> 00:28:45.787
AUDIENCE: No.

00:28:45.787 --> 00:28:47.620
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: You
know from experience

00:28:47.620 --> 00:28:50.650
that water does not burn
under these conditions.

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:52.950
So I will tell you
what's in this jar.

00:28:52.950 --> 00:28:54.790
This clear and
colorless liquid is

00:28:54.790 --> 00:28:59.800
a mixture of rubbing alcohol
and water, isopropyl alcohol

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:01.030
and water.

00:29:01.030 --> 00:29:05.680
You know also from experience
that when you burn alcohol,

00:29:05.680 --> 00:29:07.917
what color flame do you see?

00:29:07.917 --> 00:29:08.750
It's kind of bluish.

00:29:08.750 --> 00:29:10.745
Do you remember what
color flame you saw here?

00:29:10.745 --> 00:29:13.040
It was a little yellowish.

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:16.010
That's because we also added a
little bit of sodium chloride

00:29:16.010 --> 00:29:16.970
in there.

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:19.370
The eye is more sensitive
to the yellow color

00:29:19.370 --> 00:29:21.150
than it is to the blue color.

00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:24.380
So we added the sodium chloride
to enhance the visibility

00:29:24.380 --> 00:29:26.120
of what's going on.

00:29:26.120 --> 00:29:29.480
How can sodium chloride
enhance the visibility?

00:29:29.480 --> 00:29:32.725
So we're exciting the
electrons and the sodium ions.

00:29:32.725 --> 00:29:34.100
They go to a higher
energy state.

00:29:34.100 --> 00:29:35.300
Do you remember all the
stuff that you learned

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:37.040
in atomic structure, and so on?

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:38.330
Make connections.

00:29:38.330 --> 00:29:39.960
Make connections with that.

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:44.600
So I give you back
this dollar bill

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:47.000
because I said I
would borrow it.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:47.960
So here it is.

00:29:47.960 --> 00:29:51.417
So what does it feel like?

00:29:51.417 --> 00:29:52.250
Of course, it's wet.

00:29:52.250 --> 00:29:55.400
It's 50% water, 50% alcohol.

00:29:55.400 --> 00:29:57.230
So wait a little
bit until it dries.

00:29:57.230 --> 00:29:58.010
And then you can--

00:29:58.010 --> 00:29:59.000
so thank you very much.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.135
Give her a hand for
helping out with this.

00:30:01.135 --> 00:30:02.760
[APPLAUSE]

00:30:03.260 --> 00:30:06.890
So when you burn something
that has carbon in it,

00:30:06.890 --> 00:30:08.940
you get carbon dioxide.

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:11.270
Carbon dioxide is a gas
at room temperature.

00:30:11.270 --> 00:30:14.090
We can't see it because
it has no color.

00:30:14.090 --> 00:30:17.120
And we can't smell it
because it has no odor.

00:30:17.120 --> 00:30:19.730
But everyone knows
about carbon dioxide gas

00:30:19.730 --> 00:30:22.890
because you know about
carbonated beverages.

00:30:22.890 --> 00:30:25.470
In fact, they're called
carbonated beverages.

00:30:25.470 --> 00:30:27.150
They have carbon
dioxide in them.

00:30:27.150 --> 00:30:29.910
I'm going to do an
experiment right now

00:30:29.910 --> 00:30:33.030
so that we can learn a bit more
about how much carbon dioxide

00:30:33.030 --> 00:30:34.980
is dissolved in this liquid.

00:30:34.980 --> 00:30:37.602
And to do this experiment, I'm
going to use a baby bottle.

00:30:37.602 --> 00:30:38.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:38.810 --> 00:30:41.640
You remember that, huh?

00:30:41.640 --> 00:30:45.210
So this baby bottle has
been modified slightly.

00:30:45.210 --> 00:30:48.180
I have replaced the nipple
that has the hole in it where

00:30:48.180 --> 00:30:51.250
the milk flows out, with the
rubber bulb from a medicine

00:30:51.250 --> 00:30:52.510
dropper.

00:30:52.510 --> 00:30:54.260
And this is a very
strong piece of rubber.

00:30:54.260 --> 00:30:56.010
I'm going to try to
show you how strong it

00:30:56.010 --> 00:30:59.950
is by attempting to blow air in
it to see if I can inflate it.

00:30:59.950 --> 00:31:00.450
Here we go.

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:05.580
Can't do it.

00:31:05.580 --> 00:31:07.330
It's very, very strong.

00:31:07.330 --> 00:31:11.520
So now, please listen carefully
to this very familiar sound

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:12.990
as I open the can.

00:31:12.990 --> 00:31:15.131
You've all done this
or seen someone do it.

00:31:15.131 --> 00:31:15.630
Here we go.

00:31:15.630 --> 00:31:17.040
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:18.660
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Did you hear that?

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:21.450
Now, the can is open
to the atmosphere.

00:31:21.450 --> 00:31:23.580
That's the sound from the metal.

00:31:23.580 --> 00:31:29.350
I'm going to take the liquid
and put it in this baby bottle.

00:31:29.350 --> 00:31:31.460
What do you see?

00:31:31.460 --> 00:31:32.470
You see fizz.

00:31:32.470 --> 00:31:33.670
You see bubbles.

00:31:33.670 --> 00:31:35.959
What kind of bubbles are those?

00:31:35.959 --> 00:31:37.250
They're carbon dioxide bubbles.

00:31:37.250 --> 00:31:39.990
Where are they coming from?

00:31:39.990 --> 00:31:45.470
They're coming from the
drink, from the liquid.

00:31:45.470 --> 00:31:49.340
But the pressure now is
open to the atmosphere.

00:31:49.340 --> 00:31:50.930
And that's why
they're bubbling out.

00:31:50.930 --> 00:31:55.580
So I'm going to fill it to
the top, take the screw cap

00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:56.870
and tighten it.

00:31:56.870 --> 00:31:58.243
What should I do next?

00:31:58.243 --> 00:31:59.130
AUDIENCE: Shake it.

00:31:59.130 --> 00:32:01.630
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: You've done
this experiment before, huh?

00:32:01.630 --> 00:32:02.423
So I shake it.

00:32:06.590 --> 00:32:09.770
And now you see how much
carbon dioxide is dissolved

00:32:09.770 --> 00:32:12.440
in this carbonated beverage.

00:32:12.440 --> 00:32:14.520
There's so much carbon
dioxide in there

00:32:14.520 --> 00:32:18.380
it's able to partially inflate
this strong piece of rubber,

00:32:18.380 --> 00:32:20.720
that neither I, nor
any other human being,

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:24.324
can inflate with all
the powers of our lungs.

00:32:24.324 --> 00:32:25.740
But you already
know that there is

00:32:25.740 --> 00:32:27.750
a lot of carbon dioxide
in drinks like this

00:32:27.750 --> 00:32:31.006
because what do you do
after you take a sip or two?

00:32:31.006 --> 00:32:31.980
AUDIENCE: Burp.

00:32:31.980 --> 00:32:33.021
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Burp.

00:32:33.021 --> 00:32:34.140
Yes, you burp.

00:32:34.140 --> 00:32:37.890
When you burp, please do
it gently and politely.

00:32:37.890 --> 00:32:39.560
Your burp because the
carbon dioxide gas

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:41.250
is coming out of the liquid.

00:32:41.250 --> 00:32:43.590
So now let's see
if I can release

00:32:43.590 --> 00:32:45.630
the pressure a little bit here.

00:32:45.630 --> 00:32:47.590
I do it carefully.

00:32:47.590 --> 00:32:50.190
If I don't do it carefully,
what will happen?

00:32:50.190 --> 00:32:51.219
I will make a mess.

00:32:51.219 --> 00:32:51.760
You're right.

00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:52.770
It'll spread out.

00:32:52.770 --> 00:32:55.320
But I don't want to
make a mess because

00:32:55.320 --> 00:32:57.630
this carbonated beverage
has, among other things

00:32:57.630 --> 00:32:58.599
in it, sugar.

00:32:58.599 --> 00:32:59.640
And that sugar is sticky.

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:00.605
I don't want to have.

00:33:00.605 --> 00:33:01.230
So there it is.

00:33:01.230 --> 00:33:02.930
It's open to the atmosphere now.

00:33:02.930 --> 00:33:05.400
And the carbon dioxide
still bubbles out.

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:10.470
You know from experience that
when the drink goes flat,

00:33:10.470 --> 00:33:11.980
it doesn't taste as good.

00:33:11.980 --> 00:33:12.480
Right?

00:33:12.480 --> 00:33:13.230
Right?

00:33:13.230 --> 00:33:14.940
You're shaking your heads.

00:33:14.940 --> 00:33:17.230
Why doesn't it
taste good, as good?

00:33:17.230 --> 00:33:20.160
Because all the carbon
dioxide has disappeared.

00:33:20.160 --> 00:33:23.190
So why do we like
carbonated beverages?

00:33:23.190 --> 00:33:25.210
Some of them have
alcohol in them.

00:33:25.210 --> 00:33:28.540
Some of them have some
sugar or sweetener in them.

00:33:28.540 --> 00:33:31.920
We like them because when we
put the liquid in our mouth,

00:33:31.920 --> 00:33:34.110
the tiny gas bubbles
come out of liquid

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:35.730
and they tingle us
under the tongue

00:33:35.730 --> 00:33:38.310
and give us a
pleasant sensation.

00:33:38.310 --> 00:33:41.240
So that's about
carbon dioxide gas.

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:46.350
It is a colorless and
it is a odorless gas.

00:33:46.350 --> 00:33:49.650
Now, what I'm going to
do is an experiment using

00:33:49.650 --> 00:33:51.210
another form of carbon dioxide.

00:33:51.210 --> 00:33:52.800
It's called dry ice.

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:55.740
Dry ice is solid carbon dioxide.

00:33:55.740 --> 00:33:57.888
And you'll notice
I'm putting what on?

00:33:57.888 --> 00:33:59.640
AUDIENCE: Gloves.

00:33:59.640 --> 00:34:01.380
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Putting gloves.

00:34:01.380 --> 00:34:03.600
And I'm going to
open this bucket

00:34:03.600 --> 00:34:10.080
and pick up three chunks
of carbon dioxide, solid.

00:34:10.080 --> 00:34:12.989
This is solid carbon dioxide.

00:34:12.989 --> 00:34:17.620
It's temperature is
minus 78 degrees Celsius.

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:19.300
It's very cold.

00:34:19.300 --> 00:34:21.460
That's why I use these
gloves to protect

00:34:21.460 --> 00:34:24.190
my hands from frostbite.

00:34:24.190 --> 00:34:26.096
These gloves are not
very good insulators.

00:34:26.096 --> 00:34:28.179
But for this purpose,
they're good because I'm not

00:34:28.179 --> 00:34:29.980
squeezing on the dry ice.

00:34:29.980 --> 00:34:32.860
Dry ice changes from being a
solid to a gas by a process we

00:34:32.860 --> 00:34:34.912
call sublimation.

00:34:34.912 --> 00:34:36.370
Sublimation is
happening right now.

00:34:36.370 --> 00:34:37.203
But we can't see it.

00:34:37.203 --> 00:34:39.000
How come we can't see it?

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:41.977
Because carbon dioxide
is gas, is what?

00:34:41.977 --> 00:34:42.810
AUDIENCE: Invisible.

00:34:42.810 --> 00:34:43.500
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
It's invisible.

00:34:43.500 --> 00:34:44.489
It has no color.

00:34:44.489 --> 00:34:49.330
By the way, if you
ever see a colored gas,

00:34:49.330 --> 00:34:51.370
you run away from it.

00:34:51.370 --> 00:34:52.330
You heard me.

00:34:52.330 --> 00:34:54.940
If you ever see a colored
gas, you run away from it

00:34:54.940 --> 00:34:58.030
because all colored
gases are poisonous.

00:34:58.030 --> 00:35:00.640
All colored gases are poisonous.

00:35:00.640 --> 00:35:02.210
The converse is not true.

00:35:02.210 --> 00:35:05.170
There are some colorless gases
that are deadly poisonous,

00:35:05.170 --> 00:35:08.200
including the close
relative to carbon dioxide?

00:35:08.200 --> 00:35:09.320
AUDIENCE: Carbon monoxide.

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:10.150
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Carbon monoxide.

00:35:10.150 --> 00:35:10.650
OK.

00:35:10.650 --> 00:35:11.440
So, all right.

00:35:11.440 --> 00:35:13.870
So sublimation is
happening right now.

00:35:13.870 --> 00:35:15.710
We can't see it.

00:35:15.710 --> 00:35:18.110
And I'm going to put
those three back in here.

00:35:18.110 --> 00:35:20.750
And I ask you to focus
your attention on what you

00:35:20.750 --> 00:35:22.340
see between my two hands here.

00:35:22.340 --> 00:35:24.630
What do you see
between my two hands?

00:35:24.630 --> 00:35:25.630
AUDIENCE: Cylinders.

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:27.370
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
What shape are they?

00:35:27.370 --> 00:35:28.000
Cylinders.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:29.477
How many of them are there?

00:35:29.477 --> 00:35:30.061
AUDIENCE: Six.

00:35:30.061 --> 00:35:31.977
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: And
are they big cylinders

00:35:31.977 --> 00:35:33.020
or small cylinders.

00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:33.700
AUDIENCE: Big.

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:35.806
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Well, how big is big?

00:35:35.806 --> 00:35:36.590
This big.

00:35:36.590 --> 00:35:37.170
Yeah, I know.

00:35:37.170 --> 00:35:37.836
That's this big.

00:35:37.836 --> 00:35:39.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:40.570 --> 00:35:42.760
I'm going to ask you to
do the very same thing I

00:35:42.760 --> 00:35:47.110
ask my students in my freshman
chemistry course at Wisconsin

00:35:47.110 --> 00:35:48.220
to do.

00:35:48.220 --> 00:35:50.740
In order to sharpen your
powers of observation

00:35:50.740 --> 00:35:54.100
and develop the skills of
reporting these observations,

00:35:54.100 --> 00:35:58.570
I ask you to pretend to be the
play-by-play radio announcer,

00:35:58.570 --> 00:36:00.640
describing to someone
who is not with us what's

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:02.872
going on, not the TV announcer.

00:36:02.872 --> 00:36:05.080
That person has got it made
because the picture tells

00:36:05.080 --> 00:36:06.230
almost everything.

00:36:06.230 --> 00:36:08.402
So there are how many cylinders?

00:36:08.402 --> 00:36:09.429
AUDIENCE: Six.

00:36:09.429 --> 00:36:11.970
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: And what do
you see inside the cylinders?

00:36:11.970 --> 00:36:13.320
AUDIENCE: Colored liquids.

00:36:13.320 --> 00:36:14.080
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Colored liquids.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:14.580
OK.

00:36:14.580 --> 00:36:16.340
I'm listening to
you on the radio.

00:36:16.340 --> 00:36:19.420
And what I hear you say is
that there are six cylinders.

00:36:19.420 --> 00:36:21.340
And they have in
them colored liquids.

00:36:21.340 --> 00:36:22.150
Come on.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:24.400
Your brain learned a
lot more information

00:36:24.400 --> 00:36:27.010
than those two statements.

00:36:27.010 --> 00:36:28.710
So they're about
this big, you said.

00:36:28.710 --> 00:36:31.570
I can see you on the radio
saying, it's about this big.

00:36:31.570 --> 00:36:33.310
You've got to do
better than this.

00:36:33.310 --> 00:36:36.190
Are they 100
millimeters in size?

00:36:36.190 --> 00:36:38.530
Are they 10 liters in size?

00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:40.100
Are they somewhere in between?

00:36:40.100 --> 00:36:40.600
Yes.

00:36:40.600 --> 00:36:41.590
We put a bracket on it.

00:36:41.590 --> 00:36:44.680
When we estimate in science,
we put a bracket on it.

00:36:44.680 --> 00:36:47.000
And they have, yes,
colored liquids.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:50.070
How do you know they're liquids?

00:36:50.070 --> 00:36:50.940
They could be gels.

00:36:50.940 --> 00:36:51.780
How do we find out?

00:36:55.960 --> 00:36:57.700
We shake them up a
little bit because we

00:36:57.700 --> 00:36:58.780
know from experience.

00:36:58.780 --> 00:36:59.920
It's a keyword.

00:36:59.920 --> 00:37:00.840
We learn things.

00:37:00.840 --> 00:37:02.350
Our brain learns things.

00:37:02.350 --> 00:37:03.730
So we use them.

00:37:03.730 --> 00:37:05.440
So they're liquids.

00:37:05.440 --> 00:37:09.530
And they seem to be arranged
in some kind of order.

00:37:09.530 --> 00:37:10.705
What is the order?

00:37:10.705 --> 00:37:13.390
It's the order of the
color in the liquids.

00:37:13.390 --> 00:37:15.450
And they're arranged in pairs.

00:37:15.450 --> 00:37:17.416
This pair has what
colored liquid in it?

00:37:17.416 --> 00:37:18.040
AUDIENCE: Blue.

00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:19.015
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: This one?

00:37:19.015 --> 00:37:19.510
AUDIENCE: Pink.

00:37:19.510 --> 00:37:20.366
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: This one?

00:37:20.366 --> 00:37:20.742
AUDIENCE: Purple.

00:37:20.742 --> 00:37:21.991
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: All right.

00:37:21.991 --> 00:37:24.460
So I'm going to take
chunks of dry ice

00:37:24.460 --> 00:37:27.850
and put them in the cylinders
in a very special way.

00:37:27.850 --> 00:37:34.156
And when I get done, you tell
me what the special way is.

00:37:34.156 --> 00:37:36.790
AUDIENCE: It's blowing out.

00:37:36.790 --> 00:37:39.892
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
What's blowing out?

00:37:39.892 --> 00:37:42.270
Do you see any bubbles?

00:37:42.270 --> 00:37:43.835
What kind of bubbles are those?

00:37:52.354 --> 00:37:54.020
I wish I had a camera
and take a picture

00:37:54.020 --> 00:37:55.710
of the facial
expressions I see here.

00:38:00.370 --> 00:38:03.870
A lot of interesting
things are happening.

00:38:03.870 --> 00:38:05.012
How interesting are they?

00:38:05.012 --> 00:38:06.720
Are they interesting
enough that you want

00:38:06.720 --> 00:38:08.110
to ask questions about them?

00:38:08.110 --> 00:38:08.450
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:38:08.450 --> 00:38:09.180
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Yeah.

00:38:09.180 --> 00:38:10.770
Well, you want to
know what's in there?

00:38:10.770 --> 00:38:12.686
You already know what's
in there, the dry ice.

00:38:12.686 --> 00:38:14.310
I put the dry ice in there.

00:38:14.310 --> 00:38:15.915
What did I put the dry ice into?

00:38:15.915 --> 00:38:18.900
Into the cylinders that have
colored liquids in them.

00:38:18.900 --> 00:38:20.920
And I put the dry ice
in every other cylinder.

00:38:20.920 --> 00:38:22.560
I didn't put it
in every cylinder

00:38:22.560 --> 00:38:24.720
right, every other
cylinder, leaving one

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:26.030
for comparison purposes.

00:38:26.030 --> 00:38:27.840
So these are dyes.

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:30.630
They'll change color when
the pH of the liquid changes.

00:38:30.630 --> 00:38:34.230
Because carbon dioxide gas in
water gives us carbonic acid.

00:38:34.230 --> 00:38:37.201
Every time we drink a carbonated
beverage, we're drinking acid.

00:38:37.201 --> 00:38:37.950
Did you know that?

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:40.800
That's a weak acid.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:43.540
But these cylinders have
in them a little bit

00:38:43.540 --> 00:38:48.410
of sodium hydroxide, before
I did the experiment.

00:38:48.410 --> 00:38:51.820
And they changed color because
carbon dioxide, the gas,

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:55.240
combines with the
base that's in there.

00:38:55.240 --> 00:38:57.830
And the dyes are
acid/base indicators.

00:38:57.830 --> 00:39:03.580
So this pair had an indicator
called bromothymol blue.

00:39:03.580 --> 00:39:05.050
This has phenolphthalein.

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:07.940
And this had a
mixture of indicators.

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:10.600
So in this pair, the color
changed from what to what?

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:12.040
AUDIENCE: Blue to yellow.

00:39:12.040 --> 00:39:13.498
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
How about this?

00:39:13.498 --> 00:39:14.570
AUDIENCE: Pink to--

00:39:14.570 --> 00:39:15.736
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: To what?

00:39:15.736 --> 00:39:16.417
AUDIENCE: Clear.

00:39:16.417 --> 00:39:17.500
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Clear.

00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:19.150
This is a clear
and colored liquid.

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:20.170
This is a clear--

00:39:20.170 --> 00:39:22.450
this is colorless, your right.

00:39:22.450 --> 00:39:24.420
Clear and colorless do
not mean the same thing.

00:39:24.420 --> 00:39:26.110
From now on, no one
in this audience

00:39:26.110 --> 00:39:28.972
is going to confuse the words
"clear" and "colorless."

00:39:28.972 --> 00:39:30.430
This is a clear
and colored liquid.

00:39:30.430 --> 00:39:32.260
This is a clear and colorless.

00:39:32.260 --> 00:39:37.560
So now I ask you to focus your
attention on this cylinder.

00:39:37.560 --> 00:39:39.760
Actually, you can
focus your attention

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:42.070
on anything you want to.

00:39:42.070 --> 00:39:44.220
You can even not pay
attention if you want to.

00:39:44.220 --> 00:39:46.450
We live in a free country.

00:39:46.450 --> 00:39:48.960
But if you want to follow
the experiment with me,

00:39:48.960 --> 00:39:51.040
I want you to focus your
attention on this one.

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:53.740
And tell me, count them out,
how many different color changes

00:39:53.740 --> 00:39:57.754
you see as I drop
the dry ice in there?

00:39:57.754 --> 00:39:59.245
[BUBBLING]

00:40:04.220 --> 00:40:05.826
I'm listening to
you on the radio.

00:40:05.826 --> 00:40:06.580
AUDIENCE: Wow.

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:07.700
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: One.

00:40:07.700 --> 00:40:08.570
Wow, I heard wow.

00:40:08.570 --> 00:40:11.081
What kind of a count is that?

00:40:11.081 --> 00:40:12.990
AUDIENCE: Three.

00:40:12.990 --> 00:40:14.670
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Three so far?

00:40:14.670 --> 00:40:16.151
Three different color changes.

00:40:16.151 --> 00:40:18.150
But you know, I'm listening
to you on the radio.

00:40:18.150 --> 00:40:21.850
And you want me to appreciate
what you're seeing.

00:40:21.850 --> 00:40:24.390
So what were the color
changes that you saw?

00:40:24.390 --> 00:40:25.980
Why couldn't you say those?

00:40:25.980 --> 00:40:29.100
You see how we have
to help our brain make

00:40:29.100 --> 00:40:32.910
the right observations and
make the right reporting.

00:40:32.910 --> 00:40:35.160
So what about this stuff
that's coming off of the top?

00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:37.790
What does it look like?

00:40:37.790 --> 00:40:38.730
AUDIENCE: Gas.

00:40:38.730 --> 00:40:40.313
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
It looks like gas.

00:40:40.313 --> 00:40:41.450
But actually what it is--

00:40:41.450 --> 00:40:42.283
it looks like smoke.

00:40:42.283 --> 00:40:43.340
But it's not smoke.

00:40:43.340 --> 00:40:46.097
What's the name of the stuff
that floats up in the sky.

00:40:46.097 --> 00:40:46.930
You can just say it.

00:40:46.930 --> 00:40:47.710
You don't have to
raise your hand.

00:40:47.710 --> 00:40:48.380
Just say it.

00:40:48.380 --> 00:40:48.730
AUDIENCE: Clouds.

00:40:48.730 --> 00:40:49.540
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Clouds.

00:40:49.540 --> 00:40:50.170
It's a fog.

00:40:50.170 --> 00:40:50.950
It's fog.

00:40:50.950 --> 00:40:52.270
It's a mist.

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:53.980
It's condensed water vapor.

00:40:53.980 --> 00:40:57.490
The condensation is taking place
on the cold carbon dioxide gas

00:40:57.490 --> 00:41:00.520
bubbles that are coming from
the sublimation process.

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:04.480
That's why sublimation is
happening right now, right

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:06.130
here, and also in this bucket.

00:41:06.130 --> 00:41:07.240
But we can't see it.

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:08.880
But over here we can
see it because gas

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:10.582
is mixing with what here?

00:41:10.582 --> 00:41:11.290
AUDIENCE: Liquid.

00:41:11.290 --> 00:41:11.383
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Liquid.

00:41:11.383 --> 00:41:12.892
And here gas is
mixing with what?

00:41:12.892 --> 00:41:13.475
AUDIENCE: Gas.

00:41:13.475 --> 00:41:13.930
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Gas.

00:41:13.930 --> 00:41:14.500
OK.

00:41:14.500 --> 00:41:20.740
So I always think, T-H-I-N-K,
T-H-I-N-K, remember that.

00:41:20.740 --> 00:41:23.160
If you remember anything
about my visit with you today,

00:41:23.160 --> 00:41:26.880
remember to T-H-I-N-K.
Remember to think.

00:41:26.880 --> 00:41:28.890
So condensed water
vapor is coming out.

00:41:28.890 --> 00:41:31.470
The mist is flowing downward.

00:41:31.470 --> 00:41:34.090
Why is the mist
flowing downward?

00:41:34.090 --> 00:41:37.654
Because carbon dioxide
gas is denser than air.

00:41:37.654 --> 00:41:38.570
It's heavier than air.

00:41:38.570 --> 00:41:40.580
And if we knew this,
this is a beautiful way

00:41:40.580 --> 00:41:41.810
to be reminded of it.

00:41:41.810 --> 00:41:43.880
And if we didn't know
it, we just learned it.

00:41:43.880 --> 00:41:45.770
So what I'm going to do here--

00:41:45.770 --> 00:41:47.340
because she turned it off.

00:41:47.340 --> 00:41:49.590
Ah.

00:41:49.590 --> 00:41:50.130
No.

00:41:50.130 --> 00:41:52.064
I wanted it on.

00:41:52.064 --> 00:41:53.230
Let's see if it still works.

00:41:53.230 --> 00:41:56.730
So I'm going to take this
bucket, this bucket right here.

00:41:56.730 --> 00:41:58.200
It's empty except for what?

00:41:58.200 --> 00:41:59.370
AUDIENCE: Air.

00:41:59.370 --> 00:42:01.110
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
You can't see air.

00:42:01.110 --> 00:42:04.480
And I'm going to take
the hot boiling--

00:42:04.480 --> 00:42:05.310
ah, well, it's hot.

00:42:05.310 --> 00:42:06.170
I don't know if it's boiling.

00:42:06.170 --> 00:42:07.020
It was boiling.

00:42:07.020 --> 00:42:07.820
You could see it.

00:42:07.820 --> 00:42:12.090
I'm going to use my gloves now
to protect my hands from heat

00:42:12.090 --> 00:42:13.770
because I don't
want to burn myself.

00:42:13.770 --> 00:42:15.810
And I'm going to dump
this water in here.

00:42:22.430 --> 00:42:24.945
I don't want to get the
water trapped in the gloves

00:42:24.945 --> 00:42:26.570
because you know what
then will happen,

00:42:26.570 --> 00:42:28.190
what will happen
to my-- here we go.

00:42:28.190 --> 00:42:29.920
So what do you see
coming off the top?

00:42:29.920 --> 00:42:30.640
AUDIENCE: Steam.

00:42:30.640 --> 00:42:32.265
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Steam is invisible.

00:42:32.265 --> 00:42:33.190
You can't see steam.

00:42:33.190 --> 00:42:34.060
What are you seeing?

00:42:34.060 --> 00:42:35.050
AUDIENCE: Water vapor.

00:42:35.050 --> 00:42:35.840
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Water vapor.

00:42:35.840 --> 00:42:37.090
This room is full
of water vapor.

00:42:37.090 --> 00:42:39.580
Otherwise, my throat would be
drier than it is right now.

00:42:39.580 --> 00:42:41.320
