00:48:30.810 --> 00:48:32.280
You think about that.

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:33.840
So let's see.

00:48:33.840 --> 00:48:36.410
We've got a couple of
other things going on here.

00:48:36.410 --> 00:48:38.460
What am I holding with
my two hands right here?

00:48:38.460 --> 00:48:39.450
AUDIENCE: Bottles.

00:48:39.450 --> 00:48:40.200
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
What kind of bottles?

00:48:40.200 --> 00:48:40.699
Come on.

00:48:40.699 --> 00:48:44.040
Do I have to ask all the
questions all the time?

00:48:44.040 --> 00:48:46.200
Play-by-play description, right.

00:48:46.200 --> 00:48:47.100
Are they what?

00:48:47.100 --> 00:48:48.870
What size bottles are they?

00:48:48.870 --> 00:48:50.142
What are they made of?

00:48:50.142 --> 00:48:51.434
AUDIENCE: Plastic.

00:48:51.434 --> 00:48:52.850
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Do you realize

00:48:52.850 --> 00:48:55.775
how much technology
is involved in this,

00:48:55.775 --> 00:48:56.900
in just making this bottle?

00:48:56.900 --> 00:48:58.670
Look, there's a shoulder here.

00:48:58.670 --> 00:49:00.260
There's an opening here.

00:49:00.260 --> 00:49:02.870
A lot of science and
applications of science

00:49:02.870 --> 00:49:06.510
are involved in making those
two-liter bottles, that

00:49:06.510 --> 00:49:07.590
are made of?

00:49:07.590 --> 00:49:08.450
AUDIENCE: Plastic.

00:49:08.450 --> 00:49:09.616
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Plastic.

00:49:09.616 --> 00:49:11.127
They're made of plastic.

00:49:11.127 --> 00:49:13.460
And there's a little bit of
a clear and colorless liquid

00:49:13.460 --> 00:49:15.800
near the bottom of
each one of them.

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:20.010
And I'm going to tell
you what the liquids are.

00:49:20.010 --> 00:49:23.120
The liquid in here
is hydrogen peroxide.

00:49:23.120 --> 00:49:27.170
It is 30% hydrogen peroxide, not
what you buy in the drugstore.

00:49:27.170 --> 00:49:30.740
What you buying the drugstore
is 3% hydrogen peroxide.

00:49:30.740 --> 00:49:32.690
And what do you buy it for?

00:49:32.690 --> 00:49:35.060
Because if you have a cut,
you put the hydrogen peroxide

00:49:35.060 --> 00:49:36.320
on your wound.

00:49:36.320 --> 00:49:37.430
And what do you see?

00:49:37.430 --> 00:49:38.180
AUDIENCE: Bubbles.

00:49:38.180 --> 00:49:38.540
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Bubbles.

00:49:38.540 --> 00:49:40.410
What kind of bubbles are those?

00:49:40.410 --> 00:49:42.110
They're oxygen bubbles.

00:49:42.110 --> 00:49:44.550
Because hydrogen peroxide
breaks down very,

00:49:44.550 --> 00:49:48.810
very, very, very, very, very
slowly into water and oxygen.

00:49:48.810 --> 00:49:51.470
But if there is
something that speeds up

00:49:51.470 --> 00:49:55.130
that breakup, a catalyst,
then it goes very fast.

00:49:55.130 --> 00:49:58.680
And the blood and the skin
have in them such substances.

00:49:58.680 --> 00:50:01.910
So I'm going to take what
looks like a small tea bag

00:50:01.910 --> 00:50:02.720
right here.

00:50:02.720 --> 00:50:04.130
I'm going to put it in there.

00:50:04.130 --> 00:50:09.740
And see if we can catalyze the
decomposition or the breakup

00:50:09.740 --> 00:50:12.290
of the hydrogen peroxide.

00:50:12.290 --> 00:50:16.120
You can see that already--

00:50:16.120 --> 00:50:17.370
what do you see on the inside?

00:50:17.370 --> 00:50:19.317
What do you see coming
off the top here?

00:50:19.317 --> 00:50:20.400
AUDIENCE: Condensed water.

00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:21.610
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Condensed water vapor.

00:50:21.610 --> 00:50:22.515
It's a mist.

00:50:22.515 --> 00:50:24.300
It's a mist, right?

00:50:24.300 --> 00:50:25.470
And where is it coming from?

00:50:25.470 --> 00:50:27.960
This reaction of the
breakup of the hydrogen

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:31.070
peroxide into water and
oxygen is exothermic.

00:50:31.070 --> 00:50:32.130
It gives off heat.

00:50:32.130 --> 00:50:33.860
So the water is boiling.

00:50:33.860 --> 00:50:36.150
And the boiling water,
when it hits the cold air,

00:50:36.150 --> 00:50:36.919
it condenses.

00:50:36.919 --> 00:50:38.460
And we see that
until the temperature

00:50:38.460 --> 00:50:41.340
gets to be the same as
the air temperature.

00:50:41.340 --> 00:50:42.730
And we don't see it anymore.

00:50:42.730 --> 00:50:45.240
So we always like to repeat
the experiment in science.

00:50:45.240 --> 00:50:47.010
But before I repeat
the experiment,

00:50:47.010 --> 00:50:49.260
I want you to look
very, very closely,

00:50:49.260 --> 00:50:52.860
if you haven't been doing
so already, about what else

00:50:52.860 --> 00:50:54.410
is happening to the plastic.

00:50:54.410 --> 00:50:55.710
But what is this?

00:50:55.710 --> 00:50:56.280
What is this?

00:50:56.280 --> 00:50:57.696
I'm listening to
you on the radio.

00:50:57.696 --> 00:50:59.240
I can't see this.

00:50:59.240 --> 00:50:59.820
What is this?

00:50:59.820 --> 00:51:00.580
Tell me.

00:51:00.580 --> 00:51:01.750
Tell me out loud.

00:51:01.750 --> 00:51:02.580
Huh?

00:51:02.580 --> 00:51:04.440
The plastic bottle is shrinking.

00:51:04.440 --> 00:51:06.360
Amazing.

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:08.400
When I was a student
at Boston University,

00:51:08.400 --> 00:51:10.830
I learned that if you take
a substance and you heat it,

00:51:10.830 --> 00:51:12.840
it stretches.

00:51:12.840 --> 00:51:14.130
But this is plastic.

00:51:14.130 --> 00:51:15.570
This is made by people.

00:51:15.570 --> 00:51:17.970
So plastics shrink.

00:51:17.970 --> 00:51:20.520
You all know that plastics
shrink because you've

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:21.870
heard of shrink wrapping.

00:51:21.870 --> 00:51:23.790
How does shrink wrapping works?

00:51:23.790 --> 00:51:26.490
You cover something up
with a plastic sheet.

00:51:26.490 --> 00:51:28.380
And then what do you do?

00:51:28.380 --> 00:51:29.310
You heat it.

00:51:29.310 --> 00:51:31.470
How come when we
heat plastic, it

00:51:31.470 --> 00:51:34.710
shrinks and when I heat a
piece of copper, it stretches?

00:51:34.710 --> 00:51:35.550
How come?

00:51:35.550 --> 00:51:38.510
This is not a
rhetorical question.

00:51:38.510 --> 00:51:40.730
I want to do T-H-I-N--

00:51:40.730 --> 00:51:41.750
what?

00:51:41.750 --> 00:51:44.210
"K" about this.

00:51:44.210 --> 00:51:45.860
So be thinking about that.

00:51:45.860 --> 00:51:47.810
So we repeat the experiment.

00:51:47.810 --> 00:51:51.380
We're do the
experiment right here.

00:51:51.380 --> 00:51:52.370
And there it is again.

00:51:52.370 --> 00:51:54.290
Let's see if the
same thing happens.

00:51:54.290 --> 00:51:57.470
As you're watching that, I'm
going to do now an experiment

00:51:57.470 --> 00:52:03.380
right here whereby
I have this beaker.

00:52:03.380 --> 00:52:06.500
It's volume is about
600 milliliters.

00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:08.315
And it's empty, except for?

