00:53:08.300 --> 00:53:09.540
are happening over here.

00:53:09.540 --> 00:53:11.270
So watch this.

00:53:11.270 --> 00:53:14.960
I take this clear and colorless
liquid and I put some of it

00:53:14.960 --> 00:53:17.900
in the beaker, about
a hundred milliliters.

00:53:17.900 --> 00:53:20.890
How do I know it's about
a hundred millimeters?

00:53:20.890 --> 00:53:23.927
I'm reading the markers
here, on the beaker.

00:53:23.927 --> 00:53:25.510
And I take about a
hundred millimeters

00:53:25.510 --> 00:53:27.334
of a different clear
and colorless liquid.

00:53:27.334 --> 00:53:28.750
But you don't know
it's different.

00:53:28.750 --> 00:53:29.932
They look the same.

00:53:29.932 --> 00:53:30.640
And look at this.

00:53:30.640 --> 00:53:33.000
Look what's going to happen now.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:34.464
AUDIENCE: It's yellow.

00:53:34.464 --> 00:53:35.880
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Isn't that one

00:53:35.880 --> 00:53:38.060
of the most fascinating
observations you make?

00:53:38.060 --> 00:53:40.230
You take two clear,
colorless liquids.

00:53:40.230 --> 00:53:41.500
You mix them together.

00:53:41.500 --> 00:53:45.810
And you get a yellow substance,
that is insoluble in water.

00:53:45.810 --> 00:53:48.360
And you notice what
happened over here?

00:53:48.360 --> 00:53:50.520
So this is-- this fell over.

00:53:50.520 --> 00:53:51.460
So it's pretty hot.

00:53:51.460 --> 00:53:53.190
I don't want to have it--

00:53:53.190 --> 00:53:53.719
there it is.

00:53:53.719 --> 00:53:54.510
I want to have it--

00:53:57.090 --> 00:53:58.710
it's going to fall over again.

00:53:58.710 --> 00:54:03.290
I'll prop it over here.

00:54:03.290 --> 00:54:05.270
So the little tea bag
has in it a catalyst

00:54:05.270 --> 00:54:08.420
called manganese dioxide, MnO2.

00:54:08.420 --> 00:54:09.830
It has large surface area.

00:54:09.830 --> 00:54:12.521
It catalyzed the decomposition
of the hydrogen peroxide.

00:54:12.521 --> 00:54:13.770
Is this one going to fall off?

00:54:13.770 --> 00:54:15.850
We'll wait and see.

00:54:15.850 --> 00:54:17.810
This is lead iodide.

00:54:17.810 --> 00:54:19.640
I mixed potassium
iodide solution

00:54:19.640 --> 00:54:21.320
with lead nitrate solution.

00:54:21.320 --> 00:54:23.840
So the magician never tells
you how the trick works.

00:54:23.840 --> 00:54:26.520
But in science, we like
to know what's going on.

00:54:26.520 --> 00:54:31.070
So I close these
back the same way.

00:54:31.070 --> 00:54:34.280
And now I'm going to
ask you a question.

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:38.080
I have a magnet
coated with Teflon.

00:54:38.080 --> 00:54:41.390
And it's sitting on top of a
motor, which I want to turn on.

00:54:41.390 --> 00:54:44.374
Can you see the bars spin?

00:54:44.374 --> 00:54:45.032
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:54:45.032 --> 00:54:46.490
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
And you tell me

00:54:46.490 --> 00:54:48.200
what direction is
the bar spinning

00:54:48.200 --> 00:54:49.370
when we look down at it?

00:54:49.370 --> 00:54:50.607
What direction is it?

00:54:50.607 --> 00:54:51.440
AUDIENCE: Clockwise.

00:54:51.440 --> 00:54:53.356
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: When
you look down at it--

00:54:53.356 --> 00:54:55.847
I'll slow it down a little
bit so you can see it better.

00:54:55.847 --> 00:54:56.680
AUDIENCE: Clockwise.

00:54:56.680 --> 00:54:57.600
AUDIENCE: Clockwise.

00:54:57.600 --> 00:54:59.433
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
It's spinning clockwise,

00:54:59.433 --> 00:55:00.560
what we call clockwise.

00:55:00.560 --> 00:55:02.680
Now, what I would
like you to do is

00:55:02.680 --> 00:55:05.920
to visualize that
you're not looking down

00:55:05.920 --> 00:55:07.480
at this spinning magnet.

00:55:07.480 --> 00:55:09.170
But you're looking up at it.

00:55:09.170 --> 00:55:12.190
Imagine there is a
ceiling fan up there.

00:55:12.190 --> 00:55:16.760
And it's moving in the
same direction as this bar.

00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:17.687
So what is that?

00:55:17.687 --> 00:55:20.020
Here's what some of you are
doing, is you're doing this.

00:55:20.020 --> 00:55:20.710
And you're looking up.

00:55:20.710 --> 00:55:21.580
And what do you see?

00:55:21.580 --> 00:55:22.710
What do you see up there?

00:55:22.710 --> 00:55:23.543
AUDIENCE: The light.

00:55:23.543 --> 00:55:25.240
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Counter-clockwise.

00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:28.000
You're confusing me.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:30.480
Is this my right
hand or my left hand.

00:55:30.480 --> 00:55:31.240
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:32.435
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
I'm looking up at it.

00:55:32.435 --> 00:55:33.310
It's my right hand.

00:55:33.310 --> 00:55:34.120
I put it down here.

00:55:34.120 --> 00:55:34.994
It is my?

00:55:34.994 --> 00:55:35.660
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:55:35.660 --> 00:55:38.040
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: It's
still in my right hand.

00:55:38.040 --> 00:55:40.480
You're really confusing me.

00:55:40.480 --> 00:55:42.280
What's going on here?

00:55:42.280 --> 00:55:43.930
Here's what's going on.

00:55:43.930 --> 00:55:46.000
I want everyone in the
audience, everyone,

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:48.290
stick your finger out like this.

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:50.870
And you and I are going
to rotate our fingers

00:55:50.870 --> 00:55:51.920
in a clockwise direction.

00:55:51.920 --> 00:55:52.420
Go.

00:55:52.420 --> 00:55:52.940
Clockwise.

00:55:52.940 --> 00:55:54.620
Hey, I said clockwise.

00:55:54.620 --> 00:55:56.040
What are you doing?

00:55:56.040 --> 00:55:56.850
Clockwise.

00:55:56.850 --> 00:55:57.350
Watch me.

00:55:57.350 --> 00:55:58.160
AUDIENCE: Clockwise.

00:55:58.160 --> 00:55:59.701
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
I'm doing-- look.

00:55:59.701 --> 00:56:03.380
When I turn around like this,
I'm doing it clockwise too.

00:56:03.380 --> 00:56:05.900
But when I turn around
like this, what do you see?

00:56:05.900 --> 00:56:06.740
AUDIENCE: Clockwise.

00:56:08.422 --> 00:56:10.130
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
So you have to think.

00:56:10.130 --> 00:56:11.870
You have to think
about the perspective

00:56:11.870 --> 00:56:15.200
that you have in
making observations.

00:56:15.200 --> 00:56:19.010
By the way, where does this
idea of clockwise movement

00:56:19.010 --> 00:56:20.420
and counter-clockwise come from?

00:56:20.420 --> 00:56:21.320
AUDIENCE: Clocks.

00:56:21.320 --> 00:56:21.780
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Clocks.

00:56:21.780 --> 00:56:22.321
Yeah, I know.

00:56:22.321 --> 00:56:23.337
It comes from clocks.

00:56:23.337 --> 00:56:24.389
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:24.389 --> 00:56:25.680
Where does it really come from?

00:56:25.680 --> 00:56:27.430
Do you know?

00:56:27.430 --> 00:56:29.390
AUDIENCE: The Sun.

00:56:29.390 --> 00:56:31.280
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
From the sundial.

00:56:31.280 --> 00:56:33.050
It's from the sundial.

00:56:33.050 --> 00:56:36.200
And as far as we
know, was the sundial

00:56:36.200 --> 00:56:39.320
first observed in the
Northern Hemisphere

00:56:39.320 --> 00:56:41.570
or in the Southern Hemisphere?

00:56:41.570 --> 00:56:44.540
As far as we know, it's in
the Northern Hemisphere.

00:56:44.540 --> 00:56:46.670
So I want you to
visualize, like you

00:56:46.670 --> 00:56:50.160
did with the ceiling
fan, the sundial

00:56:50.160 --> 00:56:52.086
in the Southern Hemisphere.

00:56:52.086 --> 00:56:52.621
Oh, yeah.

00:56:52.621 --> 00:56:53.120
Right.

00:56:53.120 --> 00:56:55.310
I want you to think
about that and see

00:56:55.310 --> 00:56:57.650
which direction it's going in.

00:56:57.650 --> 00:56:58.190
All right.

00:56:58.190 --> 00:56:58.970
It's moving.

00:56:58.970 --> 00:57:03.810
So now what I want to
do, two more experiments.

00:57:03.810 --> 00:57:07.850
So here's a beaker.

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:09.550
I have a question for you.

00:57:09.550 --> 00:57:13.520
Do you suppose there's a way
for me to hold this beaker up

00:57:13.520 --> 00:57:15.173
in the air without touching it.

00:57:15.173 --> 00:57:15.812
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:57:15.812 --> 00:57:17.770
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: So
let me borrow your book.

00:57:17.770 --> 00:57:20.110
Now, it's your book, Steve.

00:57:20.110 --> 00:57:21.910
I don't mean put it
on a book like this.

00:57:21.910 --> 00:57:23.530
I'm touching it right now.

00:57:23.530 --> 00:57:27.009
Do you suppose there's a way
to suspend this beaker up

00:57:27.009 --> 00:57:28.300
in the air without touching it?

00:57:28.300 --> 00:57:29.293
Yes or no.

00:57:29.293 --> 00:57:29.877
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:57:29.877 --> 00:57:31.793
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Some
of you are saying yes

00:57:31.793 --> 00:57:33.380
because you know how it's done.

00:57:33.380 --> 00:57:36.080
And some of you are saying
yes because you trust that I'm

00:57:36.080 --> 00:57:38.300
going to show you how to do it.

00:57:38.300 --> 00:57:40.580
So here's what
we're going to do.

00:57:40.580 --> 00:57:41.455
We're going to take--

00:57:44.210 --> 00:57:46.310
you're doing the
play-by-play description.

00:57:46.310 --> 00:57:47.898
What is this?

00:57:47.898 --> 00:57:48.886
AUDIENCE: A balloon.

00:57:51.850 --> 00:57:54.650
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: What else
can you tell me about it?

00:57:54.650 --> 00:57:55.858
Does it have a color?

00:57:55.858 --> 00:57:58.279
AUDIENCE: It's blue.

00:57:58.279 --> 00:57:59.320
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Look.

00:57:59.320 --> 00:58:04.330
I am told the brain receives
every second about 11

00:58:04.330 --> 00:58:07.450
million bits of information.

00:58:07.450 --> 00:58:10.070
And a brain can't sort them
all out at the same time.

00:58:10.070 --> 00:58:12.160
So we have to
train ourselves how

00:58:12.160 --> 00:58:13.737
to make observations
and report them.

00:58:13.737 --> 00:58:14.320
So here we go.

00:58:19.040 --> 00:58:21.280
Ta-da.

00:58:21.280 --> 00:58:22.630
Is the beaker up in air?

00:58:22.630 --> 00:58:23.369
AUDIENCE: Yep.

00:58:23.369 --> 00:58:24.868
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
Am I holding it?

00:58:24.868 --> 00:58:25.779
AUDIENCE: No.

00:58:25.779 --> 00:58:26.362
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:58:29.350 --> 00:58:32.530
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: So can
you explain what this is?

00:58:32.530 --> 00:58:33.850
I pulled it out.

00:58:33.850 --> 00:58:36.780
Can you explain how this works?

00:58:36.780 --> 00:58:39.450
Can you explain how this works?

00:58:39.450 --> 00:58:40.950
So I want you to
think about this.

00:58:40.950 --> 00:58:43.680
You also know what's going to
happen when I let the air out

00:58:43.680 --> 00:58:44.230
of here.

00:58:44.230 --> 00:58:45.210
AUDIENCE: Let go.

00:58:45.210 --> 00:58:46.334
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Let go.

00:58:46.334 --> 00:58:47.850
OK, I'll let go.

00:58:47.850 --> 00:58:48.870
You've done that before.

00:58:48.870 --> 00:58:50.280
Why does that happen?

00:58:50.280 --> 00:58:53.630
Lots of interesting
things happen in science

00:58:53.630 --> 00:58:56.240
with familiar items.

00:58:56.240 --> 00:58:59.850
So how do you explain
what happened here?

00:58:59.850 --> 00:59:00.450
What?

00:59:00.450 --> 00:59:01.740
You're thinking about it?

00:59:01.740 --> 00:59:07.032
Some people say that when I
inflated the balloon in here,

00:59:07.032 --> 00:59:08.490
there was a change
in the pressure.

00:59:08.490 --> 00:59:09.690
I want to tell you--

00:59:09.690 --> 00:59:11.217
you can think about that too.

00:59:11.217 --> 00:59:12.300
I didn't bring it with me.

00:59:12.300 --> 00:59:16.410
But I went to the glass shop
at the University of Wisconsin

00:59:16.410 --> 00:59:22.020
chemistry department and I sawed
off the bottom of the beaker

00:59:22.020 --> 00:59:23.760
and it still works.

00:59:23.760 --> 00:59:26.550
So it's not the change
in the pressure.

00:59:26.550 --> 00:59:28.600
But everyone here
everyone, everyone,

00:59:28.600 --> 00:59:31.680
including the little
kids, know the explanation

00:59:31.680 --> 00:59:33.420
as to why this works.

00:59:33.420 --> 00:59:35.180
But you haven't
thought about it.

00:59:35.180 --> 00:59:36.460
You haven't connected it yet.

00:59:36.460 --> 00:59:40.170
So what I'd like you to do
is take both hands right now

00:59:40.170 --> 00:59:41.965
and rub them very
fast with each other.

00:59:41.965 --> 00:59:42.960
Rub very fast.

00:59:42.960 --> 00:59:44.010
What do you feel?

00:59:44.010 --> 00:59:44.970
AUDIENCE: Friction.

00:59:44.970 --> 00:59:47.040
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
You feel friction?

00:59:47.040 --> 00:59:49.860
You feel heat, which is
the result of friction.

00:59:49.860 --> 00:59:52.950
As I said, you're like
the students in my class.

00:59:52.950 --> 00:59:54.020
So friction.

00:59:54.020 --> 00:59:55.900
So can friction be
related to this?

00:59:55.900 --> 00:59:57.319
You think about it.

00:59:57.319 --> 00:59:58.110
You think about it.

00:59:58.110 --> 01:00:02.280
So now what I want to do
is do another experiment

01:00:02.280 --> 01:00:04.230
with the balloon right here.

01:00:04.230 --> 01:00:06.866
This time, I'll take
what color balloon?

01:00:06.866 --> 01:00:07.574
AUDIENCE: Yellow.

01:00:09.579 --> 01:00:11.620
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: This
balloon has a hole in it

01:00:11.620 --> 01:00:13.376
so that doesn't work.

01:00:13.376 --> 01:00:14.125
I'll try this one.

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:21.380
I inflate the balloon,
let some air out.

01:00:21.380 --> 01:00:23.600
And then I tie it.

01:00:23.600 --> 01:00:27.230
And now I'm going to
ask you a question.

01:00:27.230 --> 01:00:31.360
Do you suppose there's a way
for me to hold this balloon up

01:00:31.360 --> 01:00:35.080
in the air without touching it?

01:00:35.080 --> 01:00:37.930
So I don't mean put it
in a beaker like this.

01:00:37.930 --> 01:00:39.280
I'm not touching it now.

01:00:39.280 --> 01:00:41.560
Do you suppose
there's a way for me

01:00:41.560 --> 01:00:45.083
to suspend this up in the air
without touching it, yes or no?

01:00:45.083 --> 01:00:45.666
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:00:45.666 --> 01:00:48.430
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Those
of you who say yes--

01:00:48.430 --> 01:00:51.640
those of you who
say yes know how

01:00:51.640 --> 01:00:53.680
it's done or trust that
I'm going to show you

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:55.150
how it's going to be done.

01:00:55.150 --> 01:01:00.010
So suppose I take this
balloon and I blow air in it,

01:01:00.010 --> 01:01:00.530
like this.

01:01:04.691 --> 01:01:06.690
That was held up in the
air without touching it.

01:01:06.690 --> 01:01:08.148
But that's kind of
hard on my neck.

01:01:08.148 --> 01:01:09.580
So suppose I take--

01:01:09.580 --> 01:01:10.530
suppose I take this.

01:01:10.530 --> 01:01:12.470
What is this?

01:01:12.470 --> 01:01:13.440
AUDIENCE: Blow dryer.

01:01:18.739 --> 01:01:20.780
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Is
the balloon up in the air?

01:01:20.780 --> 01:01:22.680
Am I touching it?

01:01:22.680 --> 01:01:23.477
AUDIENCE: No.

01:01:23.477 --> 01:01:25.560
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: What
is holding the balloon up

01:01:25.560 --> 01:01:26.408
in the air.

01:01:26.408 --> 01:01:28.120
AUDIENCE: Air.

01:01:28.120 --> 01:01:29.510
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Air?

01:01:29.510 --> 01:01:31.445
There's air right
now, but it's--

01:01:31.445 --> 01:01:33.070
now, you're going to
help me with that.

01:01:36.700 --> 01:01:37.210
Thank you.

01:01:37.210 --> 01:01:38.241
Thank you.

01:01:38.241 --> 01:01:38.740
Thank you.

01:01:38.740 --> 01:01:40.132
AUDIENCE: Go faster.

01:01:40.132 --> 01:01:41.090
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: No.

01:01:41.090 --> 01:01:43.540
I was pushing the cold one.

01:01:43.540 --> 01:01:45.340
Look, you know.

01:01:45.340 --> 01:01:47.560
Each one of you knows.

01:01:47.560 --> 01:01:49.060
What was coming out
the nozzle here?

01:01:49.060 --> 01:01:51.410
What was coming out of nozzle?

01:01:51.410 --> 01:01:54.280
A stream of air, right?

01:01:54.280 --> 01:01:56.890
A stream-- wind,
that's what it was.

01:01:56.890 --> 01:01:58.280
So here we go.

01:01:58.280 --> 01:01:59.080
So do it again.

01:02:04.930 --> 01:02:06.850
Now, watch what I do here.

01:02:06.850 --> 01:02:08.260
Watch how I turn this.

01:02:08.260 --> 01:02:10.960
Watch how I turn this
to the side like this.

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:15.510
You can see how big of an
angle you can get away with.

01:02:15.510 --> 01:02:16.390
See that.

01:02:16.390 --> 01:02:19.240
See that.

01:02:19.240 --> 01:02:20.110
All right.

01:02:20.110 --> 01:02:21.984
All right, I'll have it
back from you please.

01:02:24.440 --> 01:02:26.650
You're all thinking about
what the explanation is.

01:02:26.650 --> 01:02:28.062
Thank you.

01:02:28.062 --> 01:02:29.770
You're all thinking
about the explanation

01:02:29.770 --> 01:02:32.650
because what I'm going
to do next is take this.

01:02:32.650 --> 01:02:33.764
What is this?

01:02:33.764 --> 01:02:35.216
AUDIENCE: It's a ball.

01:02:41.024 --> 01:02:42.960
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
A Styrofoam ball.

01:02:42.960 --> 01:02:45.864
AUDIENCE: Whoa.

01:02:45.864 --> 01:02:47.330
And a balloon.

01:02:47.330 --> 01:02:50.918
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: And
a balloon, up there.

01:02:50.918 --> 01:02:52.906
Am I touching any of them?

01:02:52.906 --> 01:02:54.530
AUDIENCE: No.

01:02:54.530 --> 01:02:57.710
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: What was
holding them up in the air?

01:02:57.710 --> 01:02:59.060
Thank you.

01:02:59.060 --> 01:03:00.890
Moving air, right.

01:03:00.890 --> 01:03:01.400
Look.

01:03:01.400 --> 01:03:02.990
You all know this effect.

01:03:02.990 --> 01:03:05.600
You stand on a street
corner and a big bus

01:03:05.600 --> 01:03:07.351
goes by, what do you feel?

01:03:07.351 --> 01:03:07.850
Woo.

01:03:07.850 --> 01:03:10.160
And you're driving on a
highway and the big lorry truck

01:03:10.160 --> 01:03:11.748
passes by, what do you feel?

01:03:11.748 --> 01:03:13.152
AUDIENCE: Nothing.

01:03:13.152 --> 01:03:14.556
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:16.234 --> 01:03:17.650
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
You know what?

01:03:17.650 --> 01:03:19.870
I believe you.

01:03:19.870 --> 01:03:21.220
That's your observation.

01:03:21.220 --> 01:03:24.130
I respect you for
making an observation.

01:03:24.130 --> 01:03:28.920
But watch for it next time, OK?

01:03:28.920 --> 01:03:31.270
Now, this is a
scientific principle.

01:03:31.270 --> 01:03:34.496
You all know what
this principle is.

01:03:34.496 --> 01:03:36.120
It's named after a
Swiss mathematician.

01:03:36.120 --> 01:03:36.914
It's called--

01:03:36.914 --> 01:03:37.580
AUDIENCE: Magic.

01:03:40.702 --> 01:03:42.910
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Bernoulli's
principle, Bernoulli.

01:03:42.910 --> 01:03:43.290
Look.

01:03:43.290 --> 01:03:44.380
You all know about this.

01:03:44.380 --> 01:03:45.880
I don't want to get too
personal about this one.

01:03:45.880 --> 01:03:47.200
You took a shower this morning.

01:03:47.200 --> 01:03:48.200
You turned the water on.

01:03:48.200 --> 01:03:50.560
Did the shower curtain
move in or out,

01:03:50.560 --> 01:03:52.170
if you have a shower curtain?

01:03:52.170 --> 01:03:55.510
Sometimes we don't
have shower curtains.

01:03:55.510 --> 01:03:56.830
So there's a change.

01:03:56.830 --> 01:04:00.400
There's a stream of air that
causes things to happen,

01:04:00.400 --> 01:04:02.210
as we just saw here.

01:04:02.210 --> 01:04:04.990
So now I'm going to
do an experiment.

01:04:04.990 --> 01:04:08.080
This experiment,
with this, with this.

01:04:08.080 --> 01:04:09.700
What is this?

01:04:09.700 --> 01:04:10.617
AUDIENCE: Plastic bag.

01:04:10.617 --> 01:04:12.533
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Could
I ask you to help me

01:04:12.533 --> 01:04:13.560
with this experiment?

01:04:13.560 --> 01:04:15.220
OK.

01:04:15.220 --> 01:04:18.480
So what is it that
Lou and I are holding?

01:04:18.480 --> 01:04:19.960
A plastic what?

01:04:19.960 --> 01:04:20.770
A piece of plastic.

01:04:20.770 --> 01:04:22.008
What color is it?

01:04:22.008 --> 01:04:23.920
AUDIENCE: Blue.

01:04:23.920 --> 01:04:26.170
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Do I
have to ask all the questions

01:04:26.170 --> 01:04:27.340
all the time?

01:04:27.340 --> 01:04:28.210
AUDIENCE: No.

01:04:28.210 --> 01:04:28.710
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: No.

01:04:28.710 --> 01:04:29.560
You are asking them.

01:04:29.560 --> 01:04:30.830
You have to make
these observations.

01:04:30.830 --> 01:04:31.330
Look.

01:04:31.330 --> 01:04:33.930
How long is it?

01:04:33.930 --> 01:04:36.330
It's about what?

01:04:36.330 --> 01:04:38.610
Is it about 1 meter, 10 meters?

01:04:38.610 --> 01:04:40.440
It's 2 meters in length.

01:04:40.440 --> 01:04:42.150
I have an opening
at this end here.

01:04:42.150 --> 01:04:43.520
Do you have an opening
over there, Lou?

01:04:43.520 --> 01:04:43.900
LOU: No.

01:04:43.900 --> 01:04:44.730
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: It's sealed.

01:04:44.730 --> 01:04:45.000
OK.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:46.724
So I'm going to
change sides with you.

01:04:46.724 --> 01:04:48.640
I'm going to give you
this opening right here.

01:04:48.640 --> 01:04:49.556
You hold it like this.

01:04:49.556 --> 01:04:50.640
You got it?

01:04:50.640 --> 01:04:53.010
And I'd like you to blow
air in here so that we

01:04:53.010 --> 01:04:55.700
can count how many
breaths it's going

01:04:55.700 --> 01:04:58.186
to take her to inflate this.

01:04:58.186 --> 01:04:59.520
And don't make her laugh now.

01:04:59.520 --> 01:04:59.760
OK.

01:04:59.760 --> 01:05:00.310
Come on, go.

01:05:02.850 --> 01:05:08.210
One, two, three, four.

01:05:08.210 --> 01:05:08.840
That's enough.

01:05:08.840 --> 01:05:10.970
I don't want you
to hyperventilate.

01:05:10.970 --> 01:05:12.810
You know what
hyperventilation is?

01:05:12.810 --> 01:05:15.830
Is it related to
carbon dioxide gas?

01:05:15.830 --> 01:05:19.940
So this is what she
did with four breaths.

01:05:19.940 --> 01:05:23.600
Now, I'm going to let the
air out that you put in there

01:05:23.600 --> 01:05:26.300
and give you the closed end.

01:05:26.300 --> 01:05:30.479
And then I'm going to show
you, if you pay attention,

01:05:30.479 --> 01:05:32.270
if you pay attention,
I'm going to show you

01:05:32.270 --> 01:05:36.350
how you can inflate this
two-meter long bag with one

01:05:36.350 --> 01:05:38.866
breath.

01:05:38.866 --> 01:05:39.740
You're smiling at me.

01:05:39.740 --> 01:05:41.120
You don't believe me.

01:05:41.120 --> 01:05:42.736
Do you remember what she did?

01:05:42.736 --> 01:05:44.360
She blew into it the
same way you and I

01:05:44.360 --> 01:05:49.402
blow into a paper bag.

01:05:49.402 --> 01:05:50.860
So now I'm going
to do it this way.

01:05:50.860 --> 01:05:52.830
I'm going to open
this up like this.

01:05:52.830 --> 01:05:55.080
I lift it up a little bit
so it's about-- yeah, right.

01:05:55.080 --> 01:05:55.579
Here we go.

01:05:58.610 --> 01:05:59.928
Let go.

01:05:59.928 --> 01:06:01.410
[LAUGHTER]

01:06:02.892 --> 01:06:04.374
[APPLAUSE]

01:06:06.350 --> 01:06:08.680
Did you see how it was done?

01:06:08.680 --> 01:06:10.382
Would you like to try it?

01:06:10.382 --> 01:06:11.145
LOU: Yes.

01:06:11.145 --> 01:06:12.186
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Yeah.

01:06:12.186 --> 01:06:13.750
That's the spirit.

01:06:13.750 --> 01:06:17.552
See, Leonardo said, you
know, about experiments.

01:06:17.552 --> 01:06:19.990
So I take all the air out.

01:06:19.990 --> 01:06:22.350
And now you do it
the way I did it,

01:06:22.350 --> 01:06:24.310
not the way you did
it the first time.

01:06:24.310 --> 01:06:26.590
One long breath,
right down the middle.

01:06:26.590 --> 01:06:29.100
Whenever you're ready.

01:06:29.100 --> 01:06:30.154
Close it off.

01:06:30.154 --> 01:06:32.050
[LAUGHTER]

01:06:32.050 --> 01:06:32.620
Only one.

01:06:32.620 --> 01:06:33.130
Only one.

01:06:38.360 --> 01:06:40.570
A lot better than the
first time, right?

01:06:40.570 --> 01:06:41.670
[APPLAUSE]

01:06:42.380 --> 01:06:44.720
So here's a question for you.

01:06:44.720 --> 01:06:47.115
Do you think she has that
much air in her lungs?

01:06:47.115 --> 01:06:47.656
AUDIENCE: No.

01:06:47.656 --> 01:06:48.239
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:06:49.922 --> 01:06:52.130
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Do you
think I have that much air

01:06:52.130 --> 01:06:55.310
in my lungs to blow this?

01:06:55.310 --> 01:06:59.050
What's the explanation?

01:06:59.050 --> 01:06:59.550
What?

01:07:05.704 --> 01:07:08.120
Well, the thing-a-ma-jigger
doesn't have much in air in it

01:07:08.120 --> 01:07:09.280
right now.

01:07:09.280 --> 01:07:11.260
So look.

01:07:11.260 --> 01:07:15.460
You all know the
explanation for this

01:07:15.460 --> 01:07:18.100
because we just went through
it in the previous set

01:07:18.100 --> 01:07:20.230
of experiments.

01:07:20.230 --> 01:07:24.360
What did I blow out of my
mouth and what did she do?

01:07:24.360 --> 01:07:28.346
A stream of moving air.

01:07:28.346 --> 01:07:30.220
Remember, one of my
slides says connectivity.

01:07:30.220 --> 01:07:31.512
You make connections.

01:07:31.512 --> 01:07:33.220
You make connections
between what you see

01:07:33.220 --> 01:07:34.750
and what you already know.

01:07:34.750 --> 01:07:37.600
So a stream of
moving air creates

01:07:37.600 --> 01:07:40.300
a partial vacuum and air
comes in from the outside.

01:07:40.300 --> 01:07:42.050
That's called "what's
his name" principle.

01:07:42.050 --> 01:07:43.002
What's his name?

01:07:43.002 --> 01:07:43.906
AUDIENCE: Bernoulli.

01:07:46.620 --> 01:07:48.660
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: The
whole thing was a setup.

01:07:48.660 --> 01:07:49.350
You knew that.

01:07:49.350 --> 01:07:50.430
That's why-- OK.

01:07:50.430 --> 01:07:51.870
So here's our grand finale.

01:07:56.810 --> 01:07:58.650
Here's our grand finale.

01:07:58.650 --> 01:08:00.860
It's a repeat of
that experiment,

01:08:00.860 --> 01:08:02.340
which we're going to do.

01:08:02.340 --> 01:08:05.030
In this, you're doing the
play-by-play description.

01:08:05.030 --> 01:08:06.344
What is it?

01:08:06.344 --> 01:08:07.300
AUDIENCE: Black.

01:08:07.300 --> 01:08:09.288
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Black what?

01:08:09.288 --> 01:08:11.290
AUDIENCE: Black tub.

01:08:11.290 --> 01:08:12.540
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: Black tub.

01:08:12.540 --> 01:08:14.617
And what is this?

01:08:14.617 --> 01:08:15.408
AUDIENCE: Cylinder.

01:08:25.170 --> 01:08:28.319
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: And I take
a clear and colorless liquid

01:08:28.319 --> 01:08:29.682
from this bottle.

01:08:29.682 --> 01:08:32.147
And I put it in there.

01:08:36.082 --> 01:08:37.540
And this clear and
colorless liquid

01:08:37.540 --> 01:08:43.880
is 30% hydrogen peroxide,
35% hydrogen peroxide.

01:08:43.880 --> 01:08:44.689
And I take what?

01:08:47.489 --> 01:08:48.655
I put some of this in there.

01:08:54.479 --> 01:08:58.779
But I want to help the hydrogen
peroxide break down into water

01:08:58.779 --> 01:09:00.950
and oxygen. So what do I need?

01:09:00.950 --> 01:09:02.529
I need a catalyst.

01:09:02.529 --> 01:09:04.090
I could use manganese dioxide.

01:09:04.090 --> 01:09:06.100
But it's not the only catalyst.

01:09:06.100 --> 01:09:09.720
I'm going to use this
liquid right here.

01:09:09.720 --> 01:09:14.455
This is a clear, but
slightly colored liquid.

01:09:14.455 --> 01:09:15.330
It's slightly yellow.

01:09:15.330 --> 01:09:18.295
So I'm going to put some of that
in there and see what happens.

01:09:24.730 --> 01:09:25.720
AUDIENCE: It's yellow.

01:09:29.200 --> 01:09:30.768
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI:
What's happening?

01:09:38.750 --> 01:09:40.880
You're doing the play-by-play
description, not me.

01:09:52.260 --> 01:09:54.720
Ah, it's going out
of control here.

01:09:54.720 --> 01:09:56.591
I better put it down here.

01:10:01.950 --> 01:10:04.300
So this is that the
decomposition of hydrogen

01:10:04.300 --> 01:10:09.520
peroxide using potassium iodide
solution as the catalyst.

01:10:09.520 --> 01:10:12.910
So the different catalyst caused
a lot of different changes

01:10:12.910 --> 01:10:14.120
to happen.

01:10:14.120 --> 01:10:16.270
And this is why we
need to learn more

01:10:16.270 --> 01:10:21.850
about the science of the
familiar, which is chemistry.

01:10:21.850 --> 01:10:26.430
And I want to really
thank you for coming

01:10:26.430 --> 01:10:28.830
this afternoon-- this evening.

01:10:28.830 --> 01:10:35.080
I want to ask you one more
time, what does my T-shirt say?

01:10:35.080 --> 01:10:37.960
AUDIENCE: Science is fun.

01:10:37.960 --> 01:10:41.040
BASSAM SHAKHASHIRI: That's what
I like, enthusiasm, science.

01:10:41.040 --> 01:10:44.260
So whatever you do,
do it-- do it-- do it

01:10:44.260 --> 01:10:47.390
with a purpose in mind.

01:10:47.390 --> 01:10:52.321
Try to help the
plasticity in your brain.

01:10:52.321 --> 01:10:54.570
But it's not just your brain
that we're talking about.

01:10:54.570 --> 01:10:56.460
It's what's in your heart.

01:10:56.460 --> 01:10:59.850
Because one of the important
elements of communication

01:10:59.850 --> 01:11:03.380
is what you feel in your
heart, which is not something

01:11:03.380 --> 01:11:04.620
that was on my slide.

01:11:04.620 --> 01:11:06.150
So thank you all very much.

01:11:06.150 --> 01:11:06.900
Thank you, Steve.

01:11:06.900 --> 01:11:07.856
Thank you, Lou.

01:11:07.856 --> 01:11:09.290
Thank you, everybody.

01:11:09.290 --> 01:11:10.730
[APPLAUSE]

01:11:10.730 --> 01:11:16.250
And remember, no matter
what you do, science is fun.

01:11:16.250 --> 01:11:17.150
Thank you very much.

01:11:17.150 --> 01:11:17.650
Thanks.

01:11:17.650 --> 01:11:19.300
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

